# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-dallas-bache
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The **111th Infantry Regiment**, originally the **Pennsylvania Militia** or "**Associators**", were a Pennsylvania militia unit that fought in the American Revolution, composed of civilian males from the citizenry of Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It is one of several National Guard units with colonial roots and campaign credit for the War of 1812.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The Pennsylvania Militia often fought in conjunction with General Washington and the Continental Army along the Delaware River.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The Pennsylvania Militia is currently represented in the U.S.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Army by 1st Battalion, 111th Infantry assigned to the Pennsylvania Army National Guard's 56th Stryker Brigade Combat Team, 28th Infantry Division.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment, founded as the Associators by Benjamin Franklin in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania on 21 November 1747, is the oldest regiment in Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In February 1942, the 111th Regiment was detached from the 28th Infantry Division and re-formed as a regimental combat team in the Army Ground Forces Reserve, attached to the Eastern Defense Command at Camp Pendleton, Virginia to guard militarily important facilities in the Chesapeake Bay area.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] From this assignment, it was transferred to the Pacific Theater in late 1943.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Throughout the rest of the war, the companies of the 111th would be used as replacement or additional units in combat conditions.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The Third Battalion of the 111th was used for mopping up operations on Makin Atoll in the Gilbert Islands in December 1943.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 111th B Company was assigned to the Seventh Cavalry Reconnaissance Troop of the Seventh Division for the assault on Kwajalein Island in February 1944.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In other actions, I Company of the 111th was involved in assaulting and capturing Ujeland Atoll in the Marshall Islands in April 1944.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] And in September 1944, both the D and H Companies were assigned to the 81st Division for an attack on Peleliu and Auguar Islands in the Palaus chain.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Later, in February 1945, the entire 111th returned to Peleliu Island for mopping-up operations.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] When the war ended in September 1945, the 111th had added three battle streamers, Central Pacific, Eastern Mandate and Western Pacific, for a total of 38 on its flag.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 1st Battalion, 111th Infantry Regiment was awarded the Meritorious Unit Commendation - Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] A Gold color metal and enamel device 1+1⁄4 inches (3.2 cm) in height overall consisting of an oval Azure a reproduction of the statue of Benjamin Franklin, by R.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 111th Infantry Regiment is the only regiment in the United States Armed Forces, in any branch, that continues to employ the Franklin Flag of John Paul Jones.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The saltire is for the American Civil War service and the fleur-de-lis for World War I service.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The canton represents the shield that appeared on the "Associators'" flag, indicating the Revolutionary War service of the organization.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The silver saltire has been voided with red in similitude to the colors of the uniforms of the Pennsylvania troops as prescribed by General George Washington in 1779.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/111th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The crest is that of the Pennsylvania Army National Guard.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Portions of dialogue and some lyrics were taken directly from the letters and memoirs of the actual participants of the Second Continental Congress.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] John Adams, representing Massachusetts in the Second Continental Congress in Philadelphia, laments the body's refusal to debate his motion to declare the colonies' independence from Great Britain and instead to discuss more trivial matters.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Disliked by most of his fellow Congressmen, he frequently seeks advice and comfort from his wife, Abigail.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania, one of the few who enjoys Adams' company due mainly to their shared dream of independence, suggests someone else propose the independence resolution.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Richard Henry Lee of Virginia eagerly agrees, and he rides home to get authorization from the state legislature to do so.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Lee returns, proposes the resolution and, over the objections of John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, leader of the Conservative faction seeking reconciliation with Britain, Congress agrees to debate the question, which becomes heated as tempers flare.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Caesar Rodney of Delaware, suffering from cancer, collapses and is forced to leave during the debate, depriving Adams of Delaware's vote.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] A new delegation from New Jersey arrives and votes in favor of independence (Franklin receives word that his son William, the Royal Governor of New Jersey, has been arrested).
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Seeking to kill the motion, Dickinson successfully moves that an independence vote be unanimous on the grounds that "no colony be torn away from its mother country without its own consent." To salvage the motion, Adams asks for a postponement to draft a declaration of grievances.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] President of the Congress, John Hancock, breaks the tie vote in favor of a declaration and appoints Adams, Franklin, Roger Sherman of Connecticut, Robert Livingston of New York, and Thomas Jefferson of Virginia to a committee to write it.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Despite his determination to go home to his wife, Martha, Jefferson reluctantly agrees to be the primary writer.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] After a full week passes without Jefferson's being able to complete the task, Adams summons Martha to Philadelphia; Martha charms both Adams and Franklin, and Jefferson finishes the draft.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] To convince Samuel Chase of Maryland to support independence, Adams agrees to accept General George Washington's plea to visit the army encampment in New Brunswick, New Jersey, taking Franklin and Chase with him.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] After the members return to their lodgings, a young military courier arrives and sadly relates to Congressional custodian Andrew McNair how his two best friends were killed in battle at Lexington.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] After Adams and Franklin return from New Jersey, the Declaration is read to the full Congress, which begins accepting many amendments.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Jefferson agrees to almost all of the changes, except striking language referring to King George as a "tyrant" and objecting to slavery.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Edward Rutledge of South Carolina leads the Southern members in walking out in protest just as Chase returns with Maryland's vote supporting independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Frustrated at Adams's refusal to compromise, Franklin tells him that to achieve the primary goal of independence Adams must accept that those with opinions contrary to his will be part of their new nation.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Badly shaken, Adams again seeks counsel from Abigail, and thanks to a delivery of much-needed saltpeter from her and the delegate from Georgia's sudden decision to support independence, Adams finds the strength and will to continue.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] On the day of the vote (July 2, 1776), Adams and Jefferson agree to drop the slavery provision, and Rutledge and the other Southern states vote for independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] With Delaware divided, Rodney is brought back to support independence by majority vote of its three representatives.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Eventually, all states vote for independence except divided Pennsylvania and New York, whose remaining representative, Lewis Morris, has abstained throughout the proceedings.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] When Dickinson rises to vote against the proposal, Franklin moves that the Pennsylvania delegation be polled: he votes for independence and Dickinson votes against it, leaving the question up to James Wilson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Not wanting to be remembered for casting the decisive vote against American independence, Wilson votes in favor.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Dickinson resigns from Congress and vows to join the army to support the fight against the British, even though he believes it to be futile.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] As the members prepare to sign the Declaration of Independence on July 4, 1776, Morris receives word that his estates have been destroyed and his family moved to safety.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Despite not being authorized, Morris signs anyway.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] As McNair tolls the building's bell, one member per state signs, establishing the United States of America.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] An asterisk (*) indicates an actor or actress who was also in the original Broadway cast.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] An original motion picture soundtrack album was released in 1972 by Columbia Records on vinyl LP records.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] It contains all the musical numbers, with the exception of "Cool, Cool Considerate Men" and "Compliments".
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The soundtrack also contains the edited versions of some of the musical numbers that were presented in full on the laserdisc and DVD releases.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Although the Original Broadway Cast recording was released on CD in 1992, the film soundtrack remains unavailable in any digital format as of 2026.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Warner bought the film rights to the musical for $1.25 million.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Many members of the original Broadway cast, including William Daniels, Ken Howard, John Cullum, and Howard da Silva, reprised their roles for the film.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Ralston Hill, Ron Holgate, David Ford, Charles Rule and others repeated their roles from the Broadway production, marking their only appearances in feature film.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] This was a decision Warner made himself after feeling he made a mistake by turning down Julie Andrews for the 1964 film adaptation of *My Fair Lady* in favor of Audrey Hepburn.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Exteriors were filmed at the Warner Ranch in Burbank, California, the former Columbia Pictures backlot, where they built an entire street of Colonial Philadelphia.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Most of the Colonial sets were destroyed by a fire in the mid-1970s.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The water fountain seen during the musical number "The Lees of Old Virginia", with Ben Franklin, John Adams, and Richard Henry Lee, became known to television viewers as the fountain seen during the beginning credits of the TV series *Friends*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] This fountain still exists directly across the street from the *Bewitched* and *I Dream of Jeannie* houses.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Interiors were shot at the old Columbia studio on Gower Street in Hollywood.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] *1776* was among the final films shot at Gower Studios before the Warner/Columbia merger in 1971.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] "Cool, Cool, Considerate Men" was cut from the film prior to its release and not included on the soundtrack recording nor on the first VHS tapes and laserdiscs.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The *Los Angeles Times* stated "The song 'Cool, Cool, Considerate Men' depicts Revolutionary War–era conservatives as power-hungry wheedlers focused on maintaining wealth." According to Jack L.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Warner, the film's producer and a friend of President Richard Nixon, Nixon requested the song be removed.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Warner's attempt to comply with Nixon's demands had initially been rebuffed by director Hunt during production, only for the song to be removed in post-production while Hunt was on vacation.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Warner also wanted the original negative of the song shredded, but the film's editor kept it in storage unaltered.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] (The footage, some of physically poor quality, was restored for the DVD and Blu-Ray releases.) Trailers had already been released in theaters with the "Considerate Men" number as its centerpiece; Warner had those trailers pulled and re-edited.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] In a 2015 interview, Hunt mentioned that Warner, on his deathbed in 1978, told a friend that he regretted editing the scene, believing he had ruined the film's structure as a result.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] It was only decades later that the song was restored to the film.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] When the Broadway musical was about to be presented to Nixon at the White House in 1970, before the film was made, his staff pressed the producers to cut the song then; their request was denied.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Some of the dialogue was taken from words written, often years or even decades later, by the actual people involved, and rearranged for dramatic effect.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film particularly omits the views of the mid-Atlantic Quaker population, represented by Dickinson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] A supposed physical fight between Dickinson and Adams is portrayed, in which Dickinson calls Adams a "lawyer" as an epithet, despite the fact that Dickinson was a lawyer himself.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Despite the film's inclusion of Martha Jefferson and Abigail Adams, Dickinson's wife, Mary Norris Dickinson, was the only spouse actually present in Philadelphia during the convention.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] (Franklin's common-law wife, Deborah Read, had died a year or so earlier.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Another departure from history is that the separation from Great Britain was accomplished in two steps: the actual vote for independence came on July 2 with the approval of Lee's resolution of independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The wording of the Declaration of Independence—the statement to the world as to the reasons necessitating the split—was then debated for three days before being approved on July 4.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The vote for independence did not hinge on passages being removed from the Declaration, since Congress had already voted in favor of independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] For the sake of drama, the play's authors combined the two events.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] In addition, some historians believe the Declaration was not signed on July 4, but on August 2, 1776.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Others note that the final copy of the document was signed by the delegates over several weeks and months, commencing in July and not completed until as late as September.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The Liberty Bell in *1776* is shown being rung as the delegates were signing the Declaration on July 4; however, Independence Hall's wooden steeple was structurally unstable, and the Liberty Bell was silent, having been lowered into the upper chamber of the brick tower.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] A smaller bell, used to toll the hours, may have rung on July 8, for the public reading of the Declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Many characters in *1776* differ from their historical counterparts.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Central to the drama is the depiction of John Adams as "obnoxious and disliked." According to biographer David McCullough, Adams was one of the most respected members of Congress in 1776.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Adams's often-quoted description of himself in Congress as "obnoxious, suspected, and unpopular" is from a letter written 46 years later in 1822, after his unpopular presidency had likely colored his view of the past.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] According to McCullough, no delegate described Adams as obnoxious in 1776.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Historian Garry Wills earlier made a similar argument, writing that "historians relay John Adams's memories without sufficient skepticism", and that it was Dickinson, not Adams, who was advocating an unpopular position in 1776.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The Committee of Five appointed to write the Declaration of Independence were: Franklin, age 70 (Howard da Silva was 62 at the time of filming in 1971); Roger Sherman, 55 (Rex Robbins was 36); Adams, 41 (Daniels was 44); Jefferson, 33 (Ken Howard was 27); and Livingston, 29 (John Myhers was 49).
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Adams" say Livingston claims to have "been presented with a new son by the noble stork" to avoid writing the declaration; no such son ever existed.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] For practical and dramatic purposes, only 20 of the over 50 members of Congress present at the time are portrayed.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] This version of John Adams is, in part, a composite character, combining the real Adams with his cousin Samuel Adams, who was in Congress at the time but is mentioned as being absent in the script.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Although the play depicts Delaware's Caesar Rodney as an elderly man near death from skin cancer (which would eventually kill him), he was just 47 years old at the time and continued to be very active in the Revolution after signing the Declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] He was not absent from the voting because of health; however, the play is accurate in having him arrive "in the nick of time", having ridden 80 miles (130 km) the night before (an event depicted on Delaware's 1999 State Quarter) unaided, instead of with the help of another delegate.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Further, Richard Henry Lee announces that he is returning to Virginia to serve as governor.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] He was never governor (it was Lee's ally Patrick Henry who assumed the post at that time); his cousin Henry Lee (who is anachronistically called "General 'Lighthorse' Harry Lee", a rank and nickname earned later) did eventually become governor (and the father of Confederate general Robert E.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] John Adams was also depicted as disliking Richard Henry Lee, but according to McCullough, Adams expressed nothing but "respect and admiration for the tall, masterly Virginian." He did dislike Benjamin Franklin, contrary to what was portrayed.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Martha Jefferson never traveled to Philadelphia to be with her husband; she was extremely ill during the summer of 1776, having just endured a miscarriage.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The play's authors invented the scene "to show something of the young Jefferson's life without destroying the unity of setting." Martha is also depicted as dancing a galop or polka with Franklin and Adams, dances not introduced until the 1800s.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The real Martha Jefferson would have been seated playing the early piano Thomas purchased for her, accompanying him as he played violin.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film, like its stage counterpart, misidentifies John Morton, the deciding vote and a soft-spoken judge who only votes for the resolution to avoid being infamous for killing it, as James Wilson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The real Wilson, though he had previously studied under Dickinson earlier in his career, had by 1776 become one of the most outspoken advocates for independence, and would only later become a judge on the Supreme Court.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] His patrician WASP accent in the film is misleading, since Wilson was a Scottish immigrant whose parents were farmers, while Morton's family was from Finland.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The quote attributed to Edmund Burke by Dr.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Lyman Hall in a key scene with Adams is a paraphrase of a real quote by Burke.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The song "Cool Considerate Men" is anachronistic; the terms "right" and "left" in politics were not in use until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] John Dickinson, who is portrayed as an antagonist here, was motivated mainly by his Quaker roots and his respect for the British Constitution, having lived in England for 3 years in the 1750s.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] He was no wealthier than some members of the pro-Independence faction, and freed his slaves in 1777.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Thomas Jefferson wrote that "his name will be consecrated in history as one of the great worthies of the revolution".
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film also misses the objection some had to the Declaration's stated basis in "rights of Man" based in "natural law" derived from a supernatural being.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The Quaker-based population in the mid-Atlantic, represented by Dickinson, objected to this conception.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The musical also deviates from history in its portrayal of attitudes about slavery.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] In *1776*, after a dramatic debate over slavery, the southern delegates walk out in protest of the Declaration's denunciation of the slave trade, and only support independence when that language was removed from the Declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The walkout is fictional, as the debate over the wording of the declaration took place after the vote for independence on July 2, and apparently most delegates, northern and southern, supported the deletion of the clause.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The musical depicts Edward Rutledge as the leader of the opposition to an anti-slavery clause in Jefferson's original draft of the Declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] However, while it is known that, according to Jefferson, the clause was opposed by South Carolina and Georgia, plus unspecified "northern brethren", that is all that is known about opposition to the clause.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Rutledge was a delegate from South Carolina, but there is no historical evidence that he played any part—much less a leadership role—in the opposition to the clause.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The musical does acknowledge the complexity of the Colonial attitudes toward slavery in the dramatic song "Molasses to Rum," sung by the Rutledge character, which illustrates the hypocrisy in northern condemnations of slavery since northerners profited from the triangle trade.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The musical depicts Franklin as claiming that he is the founder of the first abolitionist organization in the New World; the real Franklin did not become an abolitionist until after the American Revolution, becoming president of the Pennsylvania Abolition Society in 1785.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] It was actually Dickinson who freed his slaves in 1776, conditionally at first, and fully by 1787 when the Constitution was ratified.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] In both the play and the film, John Adams sarcastically predicts that Benjamin Franklin will receive from posterity too great a share of credit for the Revolution.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] "Franklin smote the ground and out sprang—George Washington.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] James Wilson is portrayed as subordinating himself to Dickinson's opposition to independence, only changing his vote so that he would not be remembered unfavorably.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] In fact, Wilson was considered one of the leading thinkers behind the American cause, consistently supporting and arguing for independence, although he would not cast his vote until his district had been caucused.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The formula John Adams gives Abigail for making saltpeter—"By treating sodium nitrate with potassium chloride, of course!"—refers to various chemicals by their modern names, instead of the names used in the 1770s.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] A more historically accurate version might be "treating soda niter with potash." More accurate still would have been a detailed description of the process, involving ingredients such as manure or bat guano, but that probably would have been too long, and repulsive to audiences.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Abigail's request for pins in exchange is not frivolous.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Electroplating had not been invented yet: The common pin was subject to rusting and breakage, and so required replacement.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] At the time, pins were necessary for a wide range of crafts, creating garments and headgear (including wigs), making lace, ribbon and other trimmings and textiles.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] They also served the roles now played by paperclips and staples.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Women used them as closures or to anchor pieces of clothing.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] (Hooks and eyes existed, but like so many manufactured goods, they had to be imported.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The hook-and-eye industry was not established in the United States until the early 19th century.) The real Abigail, if dressed as in this scene in the film, would have supported the front lacing of her gown by using pins to fasten the fabric to the stiffened bodice beneath.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Vincent Canby of *The New York Times* observed, "The music is resolutely unmemorable.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The lyrics sound as if they'd been written by someone high on root beer, and the book is familiar history—compressed here, stretched there—that has been gagged up and paced to Broadway's not-inspiring standards.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Hunt's screen version of *1776* ... insists on being so entertaining and, at times, even moving, that you might as well stop resisting it.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] I've seen *1776* now four times and it may well be that the repetition has worn grey my true-blue patriotism.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The movie is a good technical copy but rather than adding to the original in any meaningful way it merely fills it out with the usual superfluity of second-hand screen work.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Peter Hunt has directed with a view to maximum expenditure of energy.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] There is absolutely no chance that anyone will go to sleep during *1776*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Most of the actors were brought to the film from the hugely successful stage version and they all know how to milk a scene for full value." Carole Kass of the *Richmond Times-Dispatch* stated that "the film, even though the conclusion is historical knowledge, is still suspenseful.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] One cares very much about the individual delegates and their votes, opting from the theater seat for freedom.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film is also a reminder that when it came to pitting the status quo against progress, Virginia was one of the first to vote for tomorrow.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] In Philadelphia, the film opened to significantly different reactions across two of its daily newspapers.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Collins of *The Philadelphia Inquirer* called the film "an affront because it trivializes a big subject without any redeeming satirical intent.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The Founding Fathers are not cut down to human size, they are reduced to subhuman dimensions.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] They are made into singing clowns whose boobish behavior somehow produces one of the most eloquent expressions of the human spirit ever to come from the hand of man." On the other hand, Joe Baltake of the *Philadelphia Daily News* called it "a pompous, roguish, disarmingly charming movie musical.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Its original freshness is retained largely because its 1969 Broadway ancestor never attained the household-word popularity of, say, *My Fair Lady* and *The Sound of Music*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Its storyline still comes across as something delightfully novel, as does its spirited score.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Unlike other stage-to-screen adaptations, this 'new' entertainment is free of the usual telltale staleness. [...] Under director Peter Hunt's guidance, the off-beat material works surprisingly well in musical form.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] A heavy hand could have been disastrous.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] In fact, even with Hunt's light touch, "1776" occasionally gives way to a sluggish stuffiness.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Some forbearance is necessary for total enjoyment.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Sherman Edwards' unusual songs remain the work's high point, especially "The Egg," "He Plays His Violin," "Sit Down, John" and the haunting "Momma, Look Sharp." Technically, the film is visually enchanting—a giant kaleidoscope of sprawling sets, period costumes and gobs of color.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The production design is equalled only by the admirable ensemble acting.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film got similarly mixed reviews in Chicago.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Roger Ebert of the *Chicago Sun-Times* gave *1776* two stars and declared, "This is an insult to the real men who were Adams, Jefferson, Franklin and the rest ...
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The performances trapped inside these roles, as you might expect, are fairly dreadful.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] There are good actors in the movie (especially William Daniels as Adams and Donald Madden as John Dickinson), but they're forced to strut and posture so much that you wonder if they ever scratched or spit or anything ...
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] I can hardly bear to remember the songs, much less discuss them.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The movie received generally positive reviews in the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Alexander Walker of the *Evening Standard* said "it ought to be heavy going and yet the surprising thing is I didn't find it so.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The energy is infectious." He also stated that "since it was written Into the record, *1776* could hardly ignore the moment when the reference to the slave trade was shamefully, but conveniently, struck out of the Declaration of Independence in order to carry the vote.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Adams—a fine role for William Daniels." It was not without its detractors in England, however.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] I only wish I could say this fidelity to the original concept actually worked, but the fact is you have to keep pinching yourself to remember that you're watching movie.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] On Rotten Tomatoes, the film has a 68% score, based on 19 reviews, with an average rating of 7.1/10.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film was the Christmas attraction at Radio City Music Hall in New York City and performed very well, grossing $1,743,978 in its first six weeks.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] It did not perform as well in its other opening engagements in Philadelphia, Boston and Washington.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] It returned to the Music Hall for two weeks starting June 3, 1976 in honor of the United States Bicentennial.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film was nominated for the Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture – Musical or Comedy but lost to *Cabaret*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] Harry Stradling Jr. was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Cinematography but lost to Geoffrey Unsworth for *Cabaret*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film was first released on videocassette, which runs 148 minutes, and on Laserdisc in the 1980s.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The Laserdisc version runs 180 minutes and is rated PG.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The DVD, issued in 2002 as a "Restored Director's Cut", runs 165 minutes.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] It trims up some scenes and contains previously unreleased scenes, including the "Cool, Cool Considerate Men" musical number and accompanying dialogue.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] However, it excludes the previously released Overture (heard on laserdisc but not in cinemas).
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] The film was released on Blu-ray from a 4K-master on June 2, 2015.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] It contains two commentaries: an all-new commentary, with director Hunt, Daniels and Howard, and also the DVD commentary with Hunt and Peter Stone only.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] With two versions: the prior "Director's Cut", and a further "extended cut" (167 minutes), the release also includes two deleted and alternative scenes with filmmaker commentary, screen tests, and original theatrical trailers.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-film] On May 31, 2022, Sony Pictures released a three-disc 50th anniversary Blu-ray.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In 1972, it was made into a film adaptation, with eight of the original Broadway actors reprising their roles.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] It has received three New York revivals: on Broadway in 1997, an Encores! concert in 2016, and a 2022 Broadway production in which the racially diverse cast was entirely made up of people who identify as female, trans, or non-binary.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In 1925, Rodgers and Hart wrote a Broadway musical about the American Revolution called *Dearest Enemy*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In 1950, another musical about the Revolution was presented on Broadway, titled *Arms and the Girl*, with music by Morton Gould, lyrics by Dorothy Fields, and book by Herbert Fields, Dorothy Fields and Rouben Mamoulian, the show's director.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Sherman Edwards, a jazz pianist and Brill Building pop songwriter who had decades prior had minor roles in Broadway musicals, began developing lyrics and libretto for a musical based on the signing of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Edwards recounted that "I wanted to show [the founding fathers] at their outermost limits.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] These men were the cream of their colonies. ...
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] They disagreed and fought with each other.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The first songs in the project were published and copyrighted by 1964.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Producer Stuart Ostrow recommended that librettist Peter Stone collaborate with Edwards on the book of the musical.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams, the outspoken delegate from Massachusetts, was chosen as the central character, and his quest to persuade all 13 colonies to vote for independence became the central conflict.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Stone confined nearly all of the action to Independence Hall and the debate among the delegates, and featuring two female characters, Abigail Adams and Martha Jefferson, in the musical.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] After tryouts in New Haven, Conn., and Washington, D.C., the show opened on Broadway at the 46th Street Theatre on March 16, 1969.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] On May 8, 1776, the Second Continental Congress, convening in Philadelphia at present-day Independence Hall, proceeds with its business.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] John Adams, the controversial delegate from Braintree, Massachusetts, is frustrated because Congress will not even debate his proposals on independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Later, Adams meets delegate Benjamin Franklin, an elderly lecherous scamp, who suggests that Adams should let another, more popular delegate propose a resolution on independence and summons the charismatic Richard Henry Lee of Stratford, Virginia.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Lee eagerly agrees to return to Virginia to procure an independence resolution from the Virginia House of Burgesses using his family's reputation and clout ("The Lees of Old Virginia").
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] As Congress is assembled, President John Hancock notes that the entire New Jersey delegation has been absent for quite some time.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] A gloomy dispatch from George Washington, commander of the Continental Army, arrives by courier and is read aloud by Secretary Charles Thomson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Shortly thereafter, Richard Henry Lee returns, bearing a resolution for independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Elated, Adams seconds the motion to open debate on the resolution.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, a conservative and royal apologist, immediately moves to table the debate.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The vote is close, but debate is ultimately approved, prompting Dickinson to denounce the desire for independence as an overreaction to petty squabbles with Great Britain.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The debate becomes more heated and personal, sparking a physical fight between Dickinson and Adams and causing Caesar Rodney to intervene; Rodney collapses from cancer.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Pro-independence Scotsman Thomas McKean escorts Rodney back to Delaware, leaving conservative George Read in control of Delaware's delegation.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Read quickly seconds Rutledge's motion to end the debate and vote on independence, knowing it is likely to fail.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] At this moment, the Reverend John Witherspoon arrives, announcing that New Jersey's legislature has deposed its royal governor, Franklin's estranged loyalist son, and has sent Witherspoon as the new delegate with explicit instruction to vote for independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams, now seeing a path to victory, pushes to proceed with the vote, since ties are broken by Hancock, an Adams ally who is also from Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Dickinson moves to require the vote for independence to be unanimous.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The vote ends in a tie, but Hancock unexpectedly votes in favor of unanimity, explaining that if the colonies are divided, the crown will pit the colonies against each other.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Knowing that Dickinson will quash the resolution if the vote proceeds immediately, Adams moves to postpone the vote to buy time to rally the needed support; he proposes that Congress draft a Declaration of Independence to build support abroad for the cause.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Again, the vote ties; this time, Hancock votes to postpone.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Before they adjourn, John Hancock appoints a committee of Adams, Franklin, Roger Sherman of Connecticut, Robert Livingston of New York, and Lee to draft the declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Lee informs the Congress that he has been appointed Governor of Virginia and departs, never to be seen again; Adams nominates another Virginian, the resident meteorologist Thomas Jefferson, who wants no part of the task as he is returning home to see his wife after six months.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Jefferson is forced to accept the task after the other four explain why they cannot or should not ("But, Mr.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams sends for Jefferson's beloved wife Martha, reasoning that if Thomas cannot return to her, she can be summoned to him and potentially break his writer's block.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] When she arrives, she refuses to speak to Adams or Franklin and spends the night with her husband.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams, alone, again exchanges letters with his wife Abigail ("Yours, Yours, Yours").
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The next morning, Franklin and Adams again attempt to engage Martha in conversation; she speaks, but tersely, and talks of her courtship with Thomas ("He Plays the Violin").
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams is delighted to find that Jefferson has written something, but instead of work on the declaration, it is a mere note asking for him and Martha to be left alone.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In June, with the Congress in what looks like a state of total lethargy, another grim dispatch from General Washington arrives, denouncing the Continental Army recruits as useless, undisciplined and outmatched, having fallen prey to numerous prostitutes at the camp in New Brunswick, New Jersey.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams, sensing that Washington is exaggerating the crisis in hopes of securing more money, convinces Samuel Chase of Maryland to go with him to New Brunswick to test Chase's fears that the Revolutionary War is doomed to end in defeat; Franklin, eager to see the prostitutes for himself, tags along.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The conservatives depart, leaving McNair, the courier (a Continental Army corporal from Watertown, Massachusetts), and a teenage "leather apron" (workman) alone in the chamber.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] As McNair begins a mock session as *president pro tempore*, he escorts the courier to Adams's seat; there, the courier and McNair discourage the leather apron from joining the Army as the courier recalls his friends' deaths at Lexington ("Momma Look Sharp").
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] As Congress reconvenes in Philadelphia, Jefferson is outside the chamber while Thomson reads the completed draft of the declaration to the Congress.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams and Franklin arrive, delighted: though the troops are indeed undisciplined, they showed exceptional shooting skill hunting waterfowl for dinner, and this convinced Chase to vote for independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] They congratulate Jefferson on his work, and Franklin compares the creation of this new country to the hatching of a bird, though they disagree on what kind ("The Egg").
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] On June 28, Hancock asks if there are any alterations to be offered to the Declaration of Independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Many delegates voice suggestions, additions or deletions.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Edward Rutledge of South Carolina objects in particular to a clause condemning the slave trade.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Rutledge leads a walk-out with the delegates from both Carolinas and Georgia, and the rest of the Congress follows.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams, who insists on including the slavery clause on principle that excluding it would make the Congress hypocrites, discusses the matter with Franklin, who tells Adams that he must accept some degree of compromise if he wants the independence resolution to pass.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams calls on Abigail in his mind to help him, and she reminds him of his commitment to the cause ("Compliments").
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Bolstered by her (and the arrival of a delivery of kegs of saltpeter he had previously requested from her), Adams recovers his energy and sends Franklin to try and win the support of Pennsylvania's James Wilson and Jefferson to talk to Rutledge.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Re-reading a dispatch from Washington, Adams, now alone, wonders "Is Anybody There?" Hall returns; after considering the words of Edmund Burke, he decides to buck his constituency's loyalist preference and use his own judgment to vote Yea for independence on Georgia's behalf.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Hancock calls for the vote on the Lee Resolution.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] At this moment, Rodney returns to Congress to assure that Delaware will vote in favor of independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Although Pennsylvania passes on their first call, the rest of the New England and Mid-Atlantic colonies vote in favor of independence except for New York, who reluctantly abstains.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] South Carolina, North Carolina and Georgia all vote "yea".
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] On Pennsylvania's second call, Dickinson is about to announce that his colony votes "nay" when Franklin requests that the delegation be polled.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Hancock proposes that no man be allowed to sit in Congress without signing the Declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Dickinson resigns but pledges his loyalty to the new nation and says he will join the army and fight on its behalf, even as he hopes for eventual reconciliation with England.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams leads the Congress in a salute to Dickinson as he leaves the chamber.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The courier arrives with another dispatch from General Washington; on the eve of the British army's looming attack on New York, Washington remarks on the bravery of his outmatched band of misfit militia members.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Washington also notes that Lewis Morris's family estate has been completely destroyed but that the Morris family was rescued and his sons joined the Continental Army.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Morris, in response, announces "To hell with New York" and agrees to sign the Declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] On July 4, McNair is sent to ring the Liberty Bell.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] It is hear ringing in the background as Thomson calls one delegate from each colony to sign the Declaration, establishing the United States of America.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The delegates freeze in position as the Liberty Bell rings to a fevered pitch.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] After out-of-town tryouts, the original Broadway production opened on Broadway on March 16, 1969, at the 46th Street Theatre (now the Richard Rodgers Theatre) and closed on February 13, 1972, after 1,217 performances.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In its three-year run, it played in three different theatres: the 46th Street, the St.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] James Theatre (1970) and, finally, the Majestic Theatre (1971).
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The principal cast included William Daniels, Howard da Silva, Paul Hecht, Clifford David, Ronald Holgate, David Ford, Virginia Vestoff and Ken Howard.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Rex Everhart, who was da Silva's understudy, replaced him on the original Broadway cast album after da Silva suffered a mild heart attack, which required him to leave the show temporarily.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Betty Buckley made her Broadway debut as Martha Jefferson in the original stage production.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Clifford David left the production soon after opening.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] He was replaced as Rutledge by David Cryer who was in turn replaced by John Cullum who became one of the few Broadway replacements in history to recreate a role on film.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The musical toured for two years in the United States and was given a London production, opening on June 16, 1970, at the New Theatre.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The production starred Lewis Fiander as Adams, Vivienne Ross as Abigail Adams, Ronald Radd, Bernard Lloyd, David Kernan as Rutledge, John Quentin as Jefferson and Cheryl Kennedy as Martha Jefferson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] An Australian production, also with Lewis Fiander, opened at Her Majesty's Theatre in Melbourne on 26 June 1971 and moved to the Theatre Royal in Sydney on 11 September 1971.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] City Center staged concert from March 30 to April 3, 2016.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The cast included MacIntyre Dixon, Ric Stoneback, and Kevin Ligon reprising their roles from the 1997 revival as Andrew McNair, Samuel Chase, and George Read respectively.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The production notably sported a racially diverse cast in light of the recent success of another musical about the Founding Fathers, *Hamilton*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The musical was produced in Chicago, Illinois by Porchlight Music Theatre as part of their "Porchlight Revisits" series in November 2018.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Directed by Michael Weber, Music Directed by Jeremy Ramey, with Musical Staging by Michelle Lauto.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The team held a two-week workshop on Zoom in April 2020, but the production was postponed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In June 2021, A.R.T. announced that the production, now directed by Jeffrey L.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Page and Paulus, would begin performances at A.R.T. in May 2022.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The cast (many of whom were making their Broadway debuts) included Crystal Lucas-Perry (later Kristolyn Lloyd) as Adams, Patrena Murray as Franklin, Elizabeth A.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Davis as Jefferson, Allison Kaye Daniel as Abigail/Rev.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Hall, Carolee Carmello as Dickinson and Sara Porkalob as Rutledge.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] A two-part radio production adapted and directed by Martin Jarvis starring Alfred Molina as Benjamin Franklin, Ioan Gruffud as John Adams.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The musical was performed in April 2026 at the Paper Mill Playhouse in Millburn, New Jersey under the direction of Mark S.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Hoebee with musical staging by Nancy Renée Braun.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The cast starred Will Blum as John Adams, Michael Burrell as Thomas Jefferson, and John Treacy Egan as Benjamin Franklin.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In the 2022 revival, the end of Act I is moved to after "He Plays the Violin".
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] According to Peter Stone, Scene Three of *1776* holds the record for the longest time in a musical without a single note of music played or sung —– over thirty minutes pass between "The Lees of Old Virginia" and "But Mr.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] On the DVD commentary, Stone says that he experimented with adding various songs in this section, but nothing ever worked.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] During this scene, dubbed "Big Three" by cast members, musicians were allowed to leave the pit, reportedly the first time in Broadway history that they were permitted to do so in the middle of a show.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Stone also notes that people often told him that, because of the subject matter and the large amount of dialogue, *1776* should have been a conventional play rather than a musical.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Stone believes that the songs create a playful, irreverent tone that helps bring the historical characters to life.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The central departure from history is that the separation from Great Britain was accomplished in two steps: the actual vote for independence came on July 2 with the approval of Lee's resolution of independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The vote for independence did not hinge on some passages being removed from the Declaration, as implied in the play, since Congress had already voted in favor of independence before debating the Declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In addition, some historians believe that the Declaration was not signed on July 4, as shown in *1776*, but was instead signed on August 2, 1776.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The authors of *1776* had the delegates sign the Declaration on July 4 for dramatic reasons.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The pro-slavery and anti-black views espoused by Rutledge in the play bear similarities to his record, though Rutledge had supported the Lee Resolution and led the campaign to convince the other South Carolina delegates to support it.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Of the four principal characters, the musical also notably focuses on Jefferson's wife, Martha, and Adams' wife, Abigail, but omits Dickinson's wife, Mary Norris, who was actually in Philadelphia, unlike the other wives, and was an active correspondent with the other Founding Fathers.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Franklin's common-law wife, Deborah Read, was deceased at this point.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams's memories near the end of his life were, according to McCullough, likely distorted and affected by his troubled tenure as President in the late 1790s; no delegate described Adams as obnoxious in 1776.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] For practical and dramatic purposes, the play depicts only 19 of the more than 50 members of Congress who were present at the time.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The John Adams of the play is, in part, a composite character, combining the real Adams with his cousin Samuel Adams, who is noted in the play as being absent.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Although the play depicts Caesar Rodney as an elderly man near death from skin cancer (which would eventually kill him), he was just 47 at the time and continued to be very active in the Revolution after signing the Declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] He was not absent from the voting because of health; however, the play is accurate in having him arrive "in the nick of time", having ridden 80 miles the night before (an event depicted on Delaware's 1999 State Quarter).
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Richard Henry Lee did not leave Congress to serve as Governor of Virginia, a post assumed at the time by Patrick Henry.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In real life, he and his brother Francis were present to sign the Declaration, and his cousin "Light-Horse Harry" Lee, mentioned in "The Lees of Old Virginia" as a general, had only reached the rank of captain by 1776.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Adams had more admiration for the "tall, masterly Virginian" Lee than the play initially implies.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Martha Jefferson never traveled to Philadelphia to be with her husband.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In fact, she was extremely ill during the summer of 1776, having just endured a miscarriage.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Jefferson rushed his work on the Declaration so he could return to Martha as soon as he could, and did so no later than August 1776, nine months before the birth of their short-lived son.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The song "Cool Considerate Men" is anachronistic, not only because of its quotation of the not-yet-written "The Star-Spangled Banner," but because the terms "right" and "left" in politics were not in use until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Dickinson, who refused to sign the Declaration based on "rights of man" and "natural law", was seeking to avoid reopening issues from the English Civil Wars, including Oliver Cromwell's Puritan regime, and the Jacobitism cause.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] In 1689, these issues had been definitively resolved in the Glorious Revolution and the constitutionalization of the English Bill of Rights based in "rights and responsibilities of person"; the word "man" is not used except in the context of treason.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The last Jacobite rebellion, seeking to re-establish Catholicism and the religious concept of "natural law", had only just happened in 1745, however.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] None of this background of Dickinson's position is depicted.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Joseph Hewes is portrayed as having little to contribute to the debates, only to consistently yield to, and vote with, Rutledge.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] According to Adams's recollections several decades later, Hewes in fact was staunchly against independence but eventually and reluctantly conceded to popular support once reconciliation appeared to be impossible.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Thomas Jefferson is depicted as saying that he has resolved to free his slaves, something he did not do, except for a few slaves freed after his death 50 years later, due to the massive debt his estate incurred and the need to keep them on the books as collateral.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Many of Jefferson's slaves, particularly the Hemings family, were related by blood to Martha (and, after Martha's death, Jefferson is believed to have fathered others); he fought to keep the family united and treated them with privileges rare for slaves of the era.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Franklin claims that he is the founder of an abolitionist organization (the Pennsylvania Abolition Society); however, he had only joined said society in 1785, nine years after the declaration.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The musical misidentifies John Morton, the soft-spoken, experienced judge who cast the deciding vote in favor of independence solely to avoid the infamy of being the single vote that vetoed it, as James Wilson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Wilson had been cautious about supporting independence at an earlier date, but he supported the resolution of independence when it came up for a vote.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Wilson was in fact one of the most outspoken political leaders of his era, as records tied to the later Constitutional Convention show, and would only become a judge after said Constitution was adopted.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The desire to not singlehandedly block the independence resolution was a joint decision of all the Pennsylvania delegates; in real life, Dickinson and another delegate agreed not to attend the July 2 vote to allow Franklin, Wilson and Morton to vote yes on Pennsylvania's behalf.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The phrase "We are about to brave the storm in a skiff made of paper", placed in the mouth of John Hancock, was actually stated by John Dickinson ("Others strenuously assert...we ought to brave the Storm in a Skiff made of Paper.") in his arguments against independence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Franklin's comments about the eagle and the turkey in "The Egg" were based on comments he had made in a 1784 letter he had written criticizing the Society of the Cincinnati for, among other perceived wrongs, using an eagle as a symbol.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Furthermore, it was not Adams who chose the eagle as the *de facto* national bird, but instead secretary Charles Thomson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The 2022 revival production includes an excerpt of Abigail Adams' March 1776 letter to John Adams, known for its "remember the ladies" statement for women's rights.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The 1972 film version of *1776* was produced by Jack L.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Warner with Hunt again directing and Stone writing the screenplay.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The film featured William Daniels as Adams, Ken Howard as Jefferson, Howard da Silva as Franklin, John Cullum as Edward Rutledge, Ron Holgate as Richard Henry Lee, and Virginia Vestoff as Abigail Adams, all of whom had performed their roles on Broadway.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The supporting cast was also mostly recruited from the Broadway production.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The principal exceptions were Donald Madden and Blythe Danner, who took over the roles of John Dickinson and Martha Jefferson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] A Director's Cut of the original film has been released on DVD and Blu-ray.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Both the look and sound of the original film have been improved through modern technology.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Many cuts to the original film by the producer Jack Warner have been restored, including verses from the songs "Piddle Twiddle and Resolve" and "He Plays the Violin" and the entire "Cool, Cool, Considerate Men,” which Warner originally cut at the urging of President Nixon.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Nixon felt the scene presented conservatism in a negative light.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Musical underscoring has been removed from several scenes without songs in order to strengthen the focus on dialogue.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Bonus material includes commentary by Director Peter Hunt and by Peter Stone, the book/screenwriter.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] Among other topics, they discuss artistic liberties and anachronisms used to dramatize the events.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/1776-musical] The musical *Hamilton* references the song "Sit Down, John!" in a lyric from the song, "The Adams Administration", in the lyric: "Sit down, John, you fat mother—[BLEEP]er." Lin-Manuel Miranda discovered the *1776* film in college and cites it as having paved the way for *Hamilton*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] It argues that an omnipotent, benevolent God is incompatible with notions of human free will and morality.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] The second portion of the pamphlet goes on to formulate that all motivations are derived from pain and that pain is met with an equal amount of pleasure.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] He then concludes that this means that man cannot be superior to animals because we are all equal in God's eyes.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] Franklin acknowledges how offensive this idea would be to the reader, and refuted it later.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] The point of the pamphlet seems to follow Calvinism.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] Franklin was raised Calvinist as a child but in his teenage years became a Deist, arguing that Calvinism cannot logically be a moral way to live.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] In 1779, Franklin came to disagree with the points he printed in *Dissertation* and burned all the copies he possessed of the pamphlet but one for historical purposes.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] However, since he had already come to give several copies to friends of his, four original copies still survive.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-dissertation-on-liberty-and-necessity-pleasure-and-pain] They are in the possession of the British Library, Library of Congress, John Carter Brown Library, and Yale University Library.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] The film was released in the United States on April 3, 2026, by Roadside Attractions.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] Benjamin Franklin, at the time of the Constitutional Convention, reminisces about his life and his long friendship with George Whitefield.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] The two had met when Whitefield preached in Philadelphia, and Franklin was astonished how far Whitefield's voice could carry.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] Whitefield partnered with Franklin in publishing many of his sermons.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] The last time they were together, Whitefield made a strong appeal to Franklin to trust in Jesus Christ for salvation.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] Franklin as a deist did not accept the divinity of Christ in that moment.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] But as he remembers Whitefield's words in 1789, he does turn to God in Christ and then goes on to call the Constitutional Convention to pray to God.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] Franklin's speech to the Convention promoting prayer is described in Concordia University's reconstruction of the Convention's daily debates.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] This is the second feature film produced by Sight & Sound Films.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] Principal photography took place in Lancaster County, including in Ronks and East Earl Township.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] Sight & Sound received $2.6 million in tax credits from the Pennsylvania Film Office, with the company expected to bring $10.4 million into the regional economy while creating and supporting 846 jobs.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] On September 30, 2025, Roadside Attractions acquired the distribution rights to the film, and released it on April 3, 2026, coinciding with the 250th anniversary of the signing of the United States Declaration of Independence, as well as *Sight & Sound'*s 50th anniversary.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] On the review aggregator website Rotten Tomatoes, 69% of 16 critics' reviews are positive, with an average rating of 5.9/10.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-great-awakening] Audiences polled by CinemaScore gave the film a rare average grade of "A+" on an A+ to F scale.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] "**A Letter to a Royal Academy**" (sometimes referred to as "**A Letter to a Royal Academy about Farting**" or "**Fart Proudly**") is the name of an essay about flatulence written by Benjamin Franklin c.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] 1781 while he was living abroad as United States Ambassador to France.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] "A Letter to a Royal Academy" was composed in response to a call for scientific papers from the Royal Academy of Brussels.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] Franklin believed that the various academic societies in Europe were increasingly pretentious and concerned with the impractical.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] Revealing his "bawdy, scurrilous side," Franklin responded with an essay suggesting that research and practical reasoning be undertaken into methods of improving the odor of human flatulence.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] The essay goes on to discuss the way different foods affect the odor of flatulence and to propose scientific testing of farting.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] Franklin also suggests that scientists work to develop a drug, "wholesome and not disagreeable", which can be mixed with "common Food or Sauces" with the effect of rendering flatulence "not only inoffensive, but agreeable as Perfumes".
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] Copies of the essay were privately printed by Franklin at his printing press in Passy.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] In the 1960s, it was included in volume 32 of the American Philosophical Society's *Papers of Benjamin Franklin*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] 1838), who, being long dead, "has graciously made no objection" to the use of his illustrations to accompany the piece.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-letter-to-a-royal-academy] In 2021, on the 240th anniversary of Franklin's letter, *MEL Magazine* commissioned a response from scientists at the Young Academy of Belgium, a department of the modern Royal Flemish Academy (and thus a successor to Franklin's Royal Academy of Brussels).
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film depicts events surrounding creation of the United States Constitution, and is focused mainly on James Madison, who wrote most of that document and took extensive notes during the convention's discussions and proceedings.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] The period immediately following the American Revolutionary War was marked by intense political unrest, owing to huge debts, the interruption of trade and business, shortages of labor, and personal turmoils, all created by the War.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] It soon became evident that the Articles of Confederation were insufficient to address the country's needs.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] A movement soon emerged to upgrade or replace the Articles, and Madison was foremost in the movement.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] However, he needed the support of George Washington, and needed to show that a new government would be sufficient to address such challenges as Shays' Rebellion and the growing trade problems between the independent States.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] Madison was strongly opposed by those who feared a strong central government, people known either as *States Rights Advocates* or as *Anti-Federalists*, such as Roger Sherman and John Dickinson.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] Madison was in favor of a bicameral congress, and envisioned each house being elected with seats allocated to states in proportion to population.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] In this he was opposed by the States Rights Advocates, and he eventually accepted the compromises necessary to address their concerns.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film highlights the basis for these compromises.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film also depicts the convention delegates' debate about the slave trade.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] The movie was filmed on location at Independence Hall in Philadelphia, in Williamsburg, Virginia, and at other historical sites.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] Much of the film is shot from the viewpoint of James Madison, with the script being based primarily on his writings.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/a-more-perfect-union-film] These include the copious minutes he took during the Constitutional Convention, which were published after his death as *Notes of Debates in the Federal Convention of 1787*.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was born in Philadelphia, the son of Richard Bache, Jr., and Sophia Burrell Dallas Bache.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] He came from a family prominent in American politics.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] He was the nephew of Vice-President George M.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Dallas, the grandson of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Dallas, and the great-grandson of Benjamin Franklin.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] After graduating from the United States Military Academy at West Point in 1825, as first in his class, he was an assistant professor of engineering there for some time.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] As a second lieutenant in the United States Army Corps of Engineers, he was engaged in the construction of Fort Adams in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache resigned from the Army on June 1, 1829.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was a professor of natural philosophy and chemistry at the University of Pennsylvania from 1828 to 1841 and again from 1842 to 1843.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] He spent 1836–1838 in Europe on behalf of the trustees of what became Girard College; he was named president of the college after his return.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Abroad, he examined European education systems, and on his return he published a valuable report.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] From 1839 to 1842, he served as the first president of Central High School of Philadelphia, one of the oldest public high schools in the United States.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1843, on the death of Professor Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler, Bache was appointed superintendent of the United States Coast Survey.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Whereas Hassler had faced continual doubts from Congress, Bache succeeded in convincing legislators of the value of geodesy in addition to geomagnetic and meteorological research.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] With many contacts, friends, and family among the nation's political and military leaders, Bache won liberal appropriations to build up his agency and greatly expand its work.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] By the mid 1850s it had become the federal government's leading scientific bureau.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1849, it began study of the Pacific Coast, which the US had newly acquired via the US-Mexico War and Oregon Treaty.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Assisted by Isaac Stevens, his number two in Washington, DC, Bache reorganized the Coast Survey so that it could complete initial mapping of the entire US coast.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] By the 1840s, a clique of leading US scientists began to coalesce around Bache with the goal of professionalizing their fields.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] They formalized with establishment of the Association of American Geologists and Naturalists in 1843 (renamed the American Association for the Advancement of Science five years later) and the Smithsonian Institution in 1846.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Informally, Bache and his circle called themselves the Scientific Lazzaroni.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Together, the groups created and enforced standards of intellectual merit with the goal of elevating the nation and its reputation.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] This meant discrediting charlatans but, at times, also denying research funding or academic appointments to others.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Perhaps most important, the groups advised and even mentored politicians and army engineers.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache would lead the AAAS until 1851 and serve on the Smithsonian's board of regents throughout his term as Coast Survey superintendent.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1863, amid the demands of the Civil War, Bache was a central figure in the establishment of the National Academy of Sciences, created by an act of Congress to provide scientific advice to the federal government.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] He was elected its first president and served in that role until his death in 1867.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] As the sectional crisis worsened through the late 1850s, Coast Survey budgets became ensnared by polarization and conflicts in Congress.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Then, the start of war in 1861 brought a stop to work along the South's Atlantic and Gulf coasts.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache withdrew Survey ships from the region so they would not fall into secessionists' hands.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] At the same time, some staff resigned to join the Confederacy.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] A number of trusted friends and Democratic allies, including senators Jefferson Davis and Stephen Mallory, would lead the rebellion — acts that Bache took as both political and personal treachery.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Yet the Civil War enhanced the Coast Survey's stature in Washington, D.C.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] By this time, the agency had amassed charts of southern harbors, rivers, and coastal terrain.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] The research gave a critical advantage to the Union navy and army.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Meanwhile, Bache continued to lead scientists to greater influence in government, helping to establish the U.S.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] He also played a central role in the founding of the National Academy of Sciences in 1863 and served as its first president.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] Official duties and private worries contributed to Bache's declining health.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] By 1864 he had suffered a stroke, which left him handicapped and unable to work without his wife's assistance.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] At the time of his death, he had served as head of the Coast Survey for 24 years.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] After the Civil War, Bache was elected a 3rd Class Companion of the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States (MOLLUS) in consideration of his contributions to the war effort.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] He married Nancy Clark Fowler on September 30, 1838, in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] She was born in Newport and died on January 13, 1870, in Philadelphia.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] She assisted in the publication of much of his work.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] They adopted one son, Henry Wood Bache (1839–1878).
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] He died at Newport, Rhode Island on February 17, 1867, from cerebral softening.
[src:alexander-dallas-bache/alexander-dallas-bache] He was buried in the Congressional Cemetery in Washington, D.C., under a monument designed by architect Henry Hobson Richardson.
